knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE)

The Portal, AZ rodent dataset provides information on all rodents sampled among 24 experimental plots in the Chihuahan Desert between 1977 and 2002. The following plot examines the total number of species over the entire observation time. While there is considerable change in total abundance among years, the most abundant species remained relatively stable. C. baileyi and D. merriami were the most abundant species present, however C. baileyi population exploded only in the late 1990s as D. merriamis abundance began to decline.

Overall, the average total number of species increased over the study period. The total average rodent population experienced a slow decline starting in the late 1980s, and then a sharp resurgence in the mid 1990s.

Most plots appear to contain fewer than 60 individuals of a particular species each year. However, C. baileyi and D. merriami exceed this threshold in several plots in various years. In particular, plot 4 had a surge of D. merriami in 1990, and C. baileyi increased in the late 1990s in plots 3, 6, 13, 18, 19, 20, 21, 22.

Plot 4 appears to host the largest abundance of species of all plots.

A boxplot of the mean abundance per experimental plot reveals a large number of outliers. A Kruskal-Wallis one way test of variance reveals that there is a significant difference among the mean species abundances per plot_id (p = 5.558716910^{-14}).

Of the top five most abundant species, C. baileyi and D. merriami are the most abundant for all experimental plots. However, there is a lot of variance in their sample numbers throughout the years.

Despite differences in plot abundance and overall abundance throughout the study period, there does not appear to be a significant relationship between the annual species abundance and the annual precipitation from 1980-1989 ( p = 0.0609431, -9.672026510^{-4}, 0.0346938, 8.120058610^{-4}, 1.756599, -1.1911277, 0.0789862, 0.2336035). Other factors need to be investigated to understand the difference in population dynamics occurring within the plot structure.

Using a Kruskal Wallace test to compare the amount of precipitation per year, there is no significant difference among sampling years (p = 0.9109054). This suggests that annual precipitation is not behind the difference in rodent population abundance.

We choose top five most abundant species and compare mean hindfoot length and weight.

This plot shows first five most abundant species and their mean weight vs.mean hindfoot lenghts. According to plot, species mean weights and hindfoot lenghts looks correlated. To test this correlation we did Kruskal-Wallis one way test. As a result, we saw a significant relationship between species mean weight between mean hindfoot length (p = 0.4060058).
